“Yes, sir. They should be on their way now, we gave them time to pack food from the mess hall.” Exactly at 05:00, Exodus assembled at the vehicle depot. Captain Xiao stood on a box and began to speak.
“We will head to the I-131 frontline base 50 miles outside of Iannolos City. We will support the ongoing siege operation and then attack Iannolos City to clear out the insurgents. We will use this as a base to advance into the mountains.” Captain Xiao explained. “Take your squad, prepare for departure.”
The squad dispersed, and each squad took a tank under the command of their squad leader. Kollen climbed onto a tank at the front of the convoy and sat with Nimichi, Cres, and two new recruits. Kollen remembered they had arrived only a few days ago, but he didn't know them well. He sat on the edge of the tank, his legs hanging down, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, and connecting it to his earphones and throat microphone.
“Hey, Kollen, did Harris still have Snowball?” Nimichi asked after they had settled in.
“You mean the chicken he stole?” Kollen recalled the scene from that morning when they had stolen a chicken from the farm. “Yes, I'm sure of it.”
Kolm looked at another tank of the Khoran army and saw Harris and his team. He caught a glimpse of a small chicken peeking around from behind Harris's backpack.
"Yes, he still keeps that chicken," Kolm replied. At that moment, the turret hatch of the tank creaked open, and the commander appeared before them.
"All tanks have departed," the commander said calmly and clearly into the earpiece. The armored platoon's tanks and Stryker armored vehicles roared to life and began moving forward. Kolm's Kroneo tank released the brake and moved forward, joining the formation. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Itanian plains. The winter blizzards had frozen the wetlands and forests, but the mud still remained.
About an hour later, a new recruit (Kolm remembered his name was Orson) asked, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the war began?"
"Yes, I've been here since the Firestorm operation started," Kolm replied. "We thought the fighting would end within a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
“It's not just an underestimate.” Nimich joined the conversation. “Their weapons and forces are beyond our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and last month they shot down the Erebus.Damn it, we should have been able to spot it on the way.”
“Well, I'll fight bravely for the Federation,” Orsen said firmly, “I won't be intimidated by those terrorists.”
“You say that now, but from what I've seen, most of you new recruits, just coming of age, run away screaming at the sound of gunfire.” Kreis said.
“Well, let's see,” Kolon laughed. Orsen said nothing more.
“Subcommander of Exodus! Commander of Exodus!” Kolon's radio equipment called out. “We have detected a thermal signal 350 yards at 20 degrees to our right forward.”
Kollen climbed onto the tank and put on his optical goggles. After switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw a heat signature in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Kollen said into the throat microphone.
"Are they enemies?" asked another new recruit, Natalie.
"Can't tell yet," Kollen said, activating the microphone. "Exodus Team, don't open fire unless attacked. Just draw them out first."
As they got closer, the faint heat signature transformed from a blurry spot into a clearer outline. One of them ran to somewhere, picked up something, and ran back to the ridge. Then, these people crouched down and took up firing positions.
“We've encountered the enemy!” Captain Xiao shouted over the radio as orange tracer fire shot up from the ridge. Bullets pinged against the tank's side, and the assault team members leaped out of the tank and took cover behind it. A anti-tank missile screamed toward them, hit the ground behind the tank formation, and exploded, sending shrapnel into one of the tanks. Another missile struck the side of an APS-Cerberus armored vehicle and exploded. After the ammunition detonated, the crew members of the armored vehicle scrambled out to find cover.
“Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 yards. Fire!” The tank platoon leader shouted over the radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 fired, and the shells screamed toward the ridge, exploding and sending dirt and rocks flying into the air.
“Send out sentry robots!” Knox shouted, still observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear door of a "Hellhound" opened, and a soldier without weapons stepped out, wearing special headphones. He spoke loudly into a square microphone, and two "Sentry" robots emerged. Their thin, metallic arms and legs moved forward quickly, and they ran swiftly. The robots were equipped with weapons, but they were all strapped to their backs.
“Kill or capture?” Kreis asked while observing.
“It looks like they want to capture the living,” Colen guessed, as the two sentry robots disappeared into the ashes and smoke. Screams and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but soon subsided. After a while, the two sentry robots returned, dragging a person with the boots of a prisoner leaving a trail on the ground. Upon reaching the safe area, the robots threw the prisoner to the ground, and he landed heavily in the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to get up, and Captain Xiao walked over. Captain Xiao turned to one of the sentries. "How many people?"
"Three are dead, sir." The sentry robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Captain Xiao nodded, then turned to Colen and Kress, who were standing nearby. "Can the two of you take this person away?"
